President Biden visited the headquarters of the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) and praised the new head of FEMA, Administrator Criswell, for her experience and leadership. He emphasized the importance of being prepared for disasters, especially with hurricane season in the south and east and fire season in the west approaching. To support this, President Biden announced that FEMA will make $1 billion available through the Building Resilience Infrastructure and Communities program to help states, territories, tribes, and rural communities invest in resilience and better protect themselves from climate events. He acknowledged the severity of last year's hurricane season and the need to be ready to protect and assist people during such crises. President Biden also highlighted the importance of FEMA's work in clearing roads, rebuilding communities, and providing essential resources to help people recover from disasters. He thanked FEMA and expressed his commitment to ensuring they have the resources they need to fulfill their mission.